Instructions¶

  • Some parts of the code are already done for you
  • You need to execute all the cells
  • You need to add the code where ever you see "#### Add your code here ####"
  • Marks are mentioned along with the cells

Face Mask Segmentation¶

Task is to predict the boundaries(mask) around the face in a given image.

Dataset¶

Faces in images marked with bounding boxes. Have around 500 images with around 1100 faces manually tagged via bounding box.

Create features and labels¶

  • Here feature is the image
  • The label is the mask
  • Images will be stored in "X_train" array
  • Masks will be stored in "masks" array

Lets use the first 400 data points to train and the remaining ones to validation set

In [7]:
#mask create
import cv2
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import preprocess_input

masks = np.zeros((int(data_train.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH))
X_train = np.zeros((int(data_train.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3))
for index in range(data_train.shape[0]):
    img = data_train[index][0]
    img = cv2.resize(img, dsize=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)
    try:
      img = img[:, :, :3]
    except:
      continue
    X_train[index] = preprocess_input(np.array(img, dtype=np.float32))
    for i in data[index][1]:
        x1 = int(i["points"][0]['x'] * IMAGE_WIDTH)
        x2 = int(i["points"][1]['x'] * IMAGE_WIDTH)
        y1 = int(i["points"][0]['y'] * IMAGE_HEIGHT)
        y2 = int(i["points"][1]['y'] * IMAGE_HEIGHT)
        masks[index][y1:y2, x1:x2] = 1

Create the model (10 marks)¶

  • Add MobileNet as model with below parameter values
    • input_shape: IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3
    • include_top: False
    • alpha: 1.0
    • weights: "imagenet"
  • Add UNET architecture layers
    • This is the trickiest part of the project, you need to research and implement it correctly
In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import MobileNet
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Concatenate, UpSampling2D, Conv2D, Reshape
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model


ALPHA = 1 # Width hyper parameter for MobileNet (0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0). Higher width means more accurate but slower

IMAGE_HEIGHT = 224
IMAGE_WIDTH = 224

HEIGHT_CELLS = 28
WIDTH_CELLS = 28

def create_model(trainable=True):
    model = MobileNet(input_shape=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3), include_top=False, alpha=ALPHA, weights="imagenet")
    for layer in model.layers:
      layer.trainable = trainable
      
    
    block = model.get_layer("conv_pw_1_relu").output
    block1 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_3_relu").output
    block2 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_5_relu").output
    block3 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_11_relu").output
    block4 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_13_relu").output

    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(block4), block3])
    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(x), block2])
    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(x), block1])
    x = Concatenate()([UpSampling2D()(x), block])
    x = UpSampling2D()(x)
    x = Conv2D(1, kernel_size=1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

    x = Reshape((IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_HEIGHT))(x)

    return Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=x)

Call the create_model function¶

In [ ]:
# Give trainable=False as argument, if you want to freeze lower layers for fast training (but low accuracy)
model = create_model(trainable = False)

# Print summary
model.summary()

Define dice coefficient function (10 marks)¶

  • Create a function to calculate dice coefficient
In [ ]:
def dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred):
    numerator = 2 * tensorflow.reduce_sum(y_true * y_pred)
    denominator = tensorflow.reduce_sum(y_true + y_pred)

    return numerator / (denominator + tensorflow.keras.backend.epsilon())

Define loss¶

In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras.losses import binary_crossentropy
from tensorflow.keras.backend import log, epsilon
import tensorflow as tf

def loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred) - log(dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred) + epsilon())

Compile the model (3 marks)¶

  • Complie the model using below parameters
    • loss: use the loss function defined above
    • optimizers: use Adam optimizer
    • metrics: use dice_coefficient function defined above
In [ ]:
# compile model
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
optimizer = Adam(lr=5e-6, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999, epsilon=None, decay=0.0, amsgrad=False)
model.compile(optimizer = optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=[dice_coefficient])

import os

folder = os.fsencode(test_images_path)
filenames = []

for file in os.listdir(folder):
    filename = os.fsdecode(file)
    if filename.endswith( ('.jpg', '.jfij') ): # whatever file types you're using...
        filenames.append(filename)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
for filenam in filenames:
  print('*' * 50)
  filename = test_images_path + filenam
  unscaled = cv2.imread(filename)
  image = cv2.resize(unscaled, (IMAGE_WIDTH, IMAGE_HEIGHT))
  feat_scaled = preprocess_input(np.array(image, dtype=np.float32))

  pred_mask = cv2.resize(1.0*(model.predict(x=np.array([feat_scaled]))[0] > 0.5), (IMAGE_WIDTH,IMAGE_HEIGHT))

  image2 = image
  image2[:,:,0] = pred_mask*image[:,:,0]
  image2[:,:,1] = pred_mask*image[:,:,1]
  image2[:,:,2] = pred_mask*image[:,:,2]

  out_image = image2
  for i in range(224):
    for j in range(224):
      for k in range(3):
        if out_image[i][j][k]>0:
          out_image[i][j][k] = 255
  print('original image')
  plt.imshow(unscaled)
  plt.show()
  print('mask')
  plt.imshow(out_image)
  plt.show()

#define dice coeff
from keras import backend as K
def dice_coef(y_true, y_pred, smooth = 1):
    """
    Dice = (2*|X & Y|)/ (|X|+ |Y|)
         =  2*sum(|A*B|)/(sum(A^2)+sum(B^2))
    ref: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.04797v1.pdf
    """
    intersection = K.sum(y_true * y_pred, axis=-1)
    union = K.sum(y_true, axis = -1) + K.sum(y_pred, axis = -1)
    dice = K.mean((2*intersection + smooth)/(union+smooth),axis=0)
    return dice

from tensorflow.keras.losses import binary_crossentropy
from tensorflow.keras.backend import log, epsilon
def loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred) - log(dice_coef(y_true, y_pred) + epsilon())



# compile model
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
optimizer = Adam(lr=5e-6, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999, epsilon=None, decay=0.0, amsgrad=False)
model2.compile(optimizer = optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=[dice_coef])


from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau
my_calls = [ModelCheckpoint("model-{loss:.2f}.h5", monitor="val_loss", verbose=1, save_best_only=True,
                             save_weights_only=True, mode="auto", period=1),
            EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss", patience=6, mode="auto"),
            ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor="val_loss", factor=0.2, patience=5, min_lr=5e-4, verbose=1, mode="auto")]

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
for filenam in filenames:
  print('*' * 50)
  filename = test_images_path + filenam
  unscaled = cv2.imread(filename)
  image = cv2.resize(unscaled, (IMAGE_WIDTH, IMAGE_HEIGHT))
  feat_scaled = preprocess_input(np.array(image, dtype=np.float32))

  pred_mask = cv2.resize(1.0*(model2.predict(x=np.array([feat_scaled]))[0] > 0.2), (IMAGE_WIDTH,IMAGE_HEIGHT))

  image2 = image
  image2[:,:,0] = pred_mask*image[:,:,0]
  image2[:,:,1] = pred_mask*image[:,:,1]
  image2[:,:,2] = pred_mask*image[:,:,2]

  out_image = image2
  print('Original Image')
  plt.imshow(unscaled)
  plt.show()
  print('Predicted mask imposed on the image')
  plt.imshow(out_image)
  plt.show()
  for i in range(224):
    for j in range(224):
      for k in range(3):
        if out_image[i][j][k]>0:
          out_image[i][j][k] = 255
  print('Mask')
  plt.imshow(out_image)
  plt.show()

Conclusions¶

  • I implemented the same mobilenet model with 2 implementations of Dice coefficient
  • In the second implementation, I added a smoothing factor to the formulae of dice coefficient.
  • I used pretrained Mobilenet architecture.
  • I used Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 5e-6 because after hyper parameter tuning manually, I find this lr very efficient in reducing validation loss.
  • A patience of 6 epochs was used for both the model implementations.

Insights about the dataset¶

  • One main thing which i found after testing with various images is our model is trained with data which has a lot of background(i.e.., person face covers less space in the whole image)
  • This was drawn because modi sir picture's mask gave a bad predicted mask when compared to the actor NTR(first picture)
  • Why the model couldn't recognize the whole mask in case of Modi sir image ? Maybe because the network did not see the data with that big bounding box.
